  "text": "YY1 binds AKT PH domain and imposes its conformational change to expose S473, which allows mTORC2 access to phosphorylate S473. This phosphorylation stabilizes the conformation leading to T308 phosphorylation and consequently full AKT activation. this regulation is likely clinically relevant, because YY1 levels correlated with pAKT(S473) in our tissue microarray studies ( Figure 1B) . Additionally, the higher correlation coefficients between YY1 and pAKT(S473) in the hormone receptor-negative breast cancer samples suggest that YY1 increase may be an indication of poor prognoses for breast cancer patients. This is corroborated by our analyses in a cohort consisting of 258 breast cancer patients [CITATION_1] , in which we observed a positive correlation between YY1 and metastatic potential ( Figure 1A) . Our data suggest that YY1 binding to the PH domain of AKT likely alters its conformation to that favoring mTORC2-mediated S473 phosphorylation. Future studies are needed to characterize this predicted conformational changes of AKT upon YY1 binding and validate our proposed model using technologies in structural and cellular biology, such as fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET). Nevertheless, our data strongly support an oncogenic role of YY1 in breast cancer, at least partially through mediating AKT phosphorylation.",
